4 - <a href="javascript:card_browser(226)">Moria Stairway</a><br>
5 - The Bridge of Khazad-dûm <br>
6 - Caras Galadhon<br>
7 - <a href="javascript:card_browser(233)">Anduin Wilderland</a> <br>
8 - <a href="javascript:card_browser(238)">Shores of Nen Hithoel</a><br>
9 - Wastes of <a href="javascript:card_browser(240)">Emyn Muil</a><br>
<br>
<b>Free Peoples (33+1)</b><br>
Arwen, Lady Undómiel x2<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(299)">Aragorn, Ranger of the North</a> x2<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(35)">Gimli, Son of Gloin</a> x2<br>
Sam, Proper Poet<br>
Elrond, Herald to Gil-Galad x2<br>
Saelbeth, Elven Councillor<br>
Golradir, Councillor from the West<br>
Erestor, Chief Advisor to Elrond<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(269)">Silinde, Elf of Mirkwood</a><br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(170)">Bounder</a><br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(256)">Gwemegil</a> x2<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(11)">Ranger&#39;s Sword</a><br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(937)">Flaming Brand</a><br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(45)">Gimli&#39;s Battle Axe</a><br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(303)">Armor</a><br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(55)">Gimli&#39;s Helm</a><br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(194)">Sting</a><br>
Vilya<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(927)">Gandalf&#39;s Staff</a><br>
Narya<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(282)">Gandalf&#39;s Cart</a> x3<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(924)">Secret Sentinels</a> x2<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(258)">The Last Alliance of Elves and</a> Men<br>
Trust Me As You Once Did x2<br>
<br>
<b>Shadow(34)</b><br>
Isengard Retainer x4<br>
Isengard Servant x4<br>
Isengard Warrior x3<br>
Isengard Smith x2<br>
Orc Commander x2<br>
Orc Overseer x2<br>
Saruman, Servant of the Eye x3<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(125)">Ulaire Enquea, Lieutenant of Morgul</a><br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(864)">Ulaire Nelya, Lieutenant of Morgul</a><br>
Isengard Axe x4<br>
Coming for the Ring<br>
Servants to Saruman x2<br>
The Tower of Orthanc x3<br>
Trapped and Alone x2    </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Strategy</Font></TD><TD> </TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN="2" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="bfont"> <b>Edit 1</b><br>
Bummer, I had no idea that at the exact time I posted this deck, it had almost already turned into a mainstream "yawn-yawn-yawn" deck.<br>
<br>
It seems that most people disapprove of my fun elements like Arwen, Lady Undomiel and Gandalf, the Grey Wizard (come on, I know it&#39;s crap to use him, but I want to!). With this in mind, here is a version that will be more viable in tournaments, though of course much more boring.<br>
<br>
<b>Remove</b><br>
Arwen, Lady Undomiel x2<br>
Gwemegil x2<br>
Elrond, Herald to Gil-Galad x2<br>
Erestor, Chief Advisor to Elrond<br>
Silinde, Elf of Mirkwood<br>
Sam, Proper Poet<br>
Gandalf, the Grey Wizard<br>
<br>
<b>Add</b><br>
Gandalf, Friend of the Shirefolk<br>
Glamdring<br>
Legolas, Prince of Mirkwood x2<br>
Elrond, Lord of Rivendell x3<br>
Bow of the Galadhrim<br>
Long-Knives of Legolas<br>
Trust Me As You Once Did (okay okay, finally the 3rd one, get off my back)<br>
<br>
What I really like with this deck is Forests of Lothlorien to really clean up minions for the double-move, but owing to the controversial reviews I&#39;ll get for posting that, guess I won&#39;t post that.<br>
<br>
<b>End Edit 1</b><br>
<br>
I have posted a deck which makes use of the Frodo signet, and everybody out there uses the Aragorn signet, so I&#39;ll concentrate one on the Gandalf signet this time.<br>
<br>
This deck revolves around skirmishing, winning them, and using Damage +1 to kill off minions to aid the double-move. Granted, you might prefer archery. I prefer archery. All of you prefer archery, in fact, and so, respect that I am posting a skirmishing deck instead of another archery deck.<br>
<br>
Your key to winning skirmishes is based fully around the Gandalf signet and <b>Trust Me As You Once Did</b>. As you have noticed, every companion in this deck possesses the Gandalf signet so you should be able to get the +3 going as long as you get just 1 companion out (Frodo and Gandalf already are). Of these companions, Arwen, already the queen of skirmishing with the Lady Undomiel version, is absolutely able to trounce minions. Aragorn can use his Defender +1 to good effect, using the bonuses to prevent an overwhelm, or even kill off the minions he faces. Likewise for Sam, Proper Poet against non-Uruks. Gimli, Gloin, already able to exert himself to +2 if necessary, uses the bonus to good effect with his Axe and Damage +2 to get rid of key minions for the double-move. Frodo...if you can boost Frodo&#39;s strength, whenever you want, wherever you want. Exhausting him to near-death to boost Frodo at Site 9 is not inhuman. It&#39;s called doing your best for the anonymous authority and not questioning it.<br>
<br>
Obviously, Gandalf can rack up the exertions pretty quick, which needs some remedy. For starters, Gandalf&#39;s Staff and Narya push him up to 6 vitality. Staff also gets him out of sticky situations for him to make others trust him as they once did in cases of large minion swarms. I used to stack Athelas on Gandalf&#39;s Cart but have abandoned it as there is the problem that Aragorn does not emerge early or the Shire Lookout Point is denied.<br>
<br>
Why the Grey Wizard? Simply because I am determined to find a use for this piece of junk. Yes, Friend of the Shirefolk is a potential 10-strength, but in this deck, Gandalf boosts, he does not really take part in skirmishes, as shown with the omission of Glamdring (I don&#39;t want to exert him anymore he can take). Grey Pilgrim is virtually useless without the King in Exile to support him. As for Grey Wizard? Look at it this way: you can play EVERY companion free except for Aragorn, and even then, he comes at a reduced cost of 2 (just remember to use the text: all your companions have the Gandalf signet, remember). And also, the fact that you have 2 companions with the Gandalf signet in your starting fellowship (Frodo and Gandalf) means that the text of Trust Me As You Once Did kicks in to near-maximum effect once it is played.<br>
<br>
Elrond serves a dual purpose for Arwen to spot her father and to heal companions (almost certainly Gandalf). Vilya allows him to heal that extra time and dump key conditions like Blade Tip, Black Breath and Trapped and Alone for shrewd strategies. Golradir and Saelbeth help out even more in skirmishes, and are there for Arwen to spot. Erestor is there because the last thing you want is for Gandalf to help your companions, only to be caught with his ugly pants down when the Hate comes knocking. Silinde is useful if you draw him early, netting you some card-draws with Nelya&#39;s help to get Site 3 to what you want if you need it. Late on, if you already have 3 Elven allies out though, pitch him.<br>
<br>
Condition-removal is not a problem though there is no Sleep. In fact, I had to remove some due to condition-overkill. Vilya and 2 Sentinels are more than sufficient to remove key conditions.<br>
<br><br>
For shadow, I wanted a culture capable of stopping power, and for amusement, one which can skirmish. Of course I thought of Uruks, but shrug, I still haven&#39;t posted an Isengard Orc half here yet. Rather straightforward, with a couple of Axes (to wreak havoc at Site 4) and Servants for surprise. It was a hard choice between Servants to Saruman and Wizard Storm - I usually go with the latter and Pass of Caradhras, but since I want a skirmish-themed deck, I will go with Servants. When Isengard Orcs win skirmishes, they get the skirmish wound and can exert for madness whereas if they lose, that&#39;s at least 2 wounds gone, more if the companion has Damage +X.<br>
<br>
Nelya is for you to switch Site 3 to Valley if you went too far. If you&#39;ve more or less already drawn all the Elves in your deck or Silinde is buried somewhere, use it for your own site control. Changing Site 7 to Wilderland is always an excellent choice.<br>
<br>
For sites, 1 fishes out one important card to cycle the deck. Bid 2. If you do get a Cart despite winning the bid, don&#39;t forget to search your deck nonetheless and stack the Cart in your hand on top of the Cart from your draw deck. One card less from your draw deck is always good. If you don&#39;t win the bid, no problem. You have 3 Carts and can live with it. Trollshaw against fuels card-draws. You have 12 possessions and artifacts capable of triggering here. Valley is really the only useful site, and can also net key card-draws with 8 Elves in the deck, and Silinde possibly abusing it. Site 4 is key. On your fellowship side, if you hopefully have drawn into some weapons by now, companions like Aragorn and Arwen are Damage +2, and Frodo Damage +1, which allows you to dice minions cleanly in skirmishes to contemplate the double-move. Your Isengard Orcs can also wreak havoc with Axes if your opponent&#39;s Fellowship did not set up quick enough, with your Servants capable of shocking your opponent if he didn&#39;t expect them, and him having to take 2 wounds. Don&#39;t except to kill though: they only just came out of the sanctuary, but it does soften them up for Tower of Orthanc and for Site 5. Site 6 for Caras Galadhon because simply, too many minions around can upset the balance of this deck. One-on-one in skirmishes, those minions stand no chance. Wilderland because simply, there&#39;s no archery involved here, and those Isengard Orcs are happy with that too. 8 for Shores for obvious reasons. 9 is really the only site useful for shadow. You&#39;d better have softened him up in 7 or 8 if you have to come to this final showdown.<br>
<br>
Hope you like this. Once again, remember that this is a skirmish-themed deck, so don&#39;t come shooting your mouths off me that it is not viable. Whether it is, judge from what I said and my card-choices.  </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP" COLSPAN="2"><font class="bfont"> <a href="/lotr/decks/decks.php">Back to Decks Directory</a> | <A HREF="/lotr/decks/decks.php?reviews=24810"> Read Reviews </A> | <a href="deckprint.php?deck=24810" TARGET="BLANK_"> Printer Friendly</a></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE><a name="review"></a><font class="h2font">In order to review decks you must be a registered member. <A href="/lotr/main/join.php">Sign up for free!</A></font></font></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_09.gif"></td></tr>
